sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Credential Manager Access By Uncommon Applications
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects suspicious processes based on name and location that access the windows credential manager and vault.
Which can be a sign of credential stealing. Example case would be usage of mimikatz "dpapi::cred" function

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Disable Microsoft Defender Firewall via Registry

A General detection for files being created in the Windows startup directory. This could be an indicator of persistence.
Detects netsh commands that turns off the Windows firewall

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Access To Windows DPAPI Master Keys By Uncommon Applications
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects file access requests to the the Windows Data Protection API Master keys by an uncommon application.
This can be a sign of credential stealing. Example case would be usage of mimikatz "dpapi::masterkey" function

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered ransomware. Other contributing factors were that it has known exploits and it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: PE32 executable (GUI) Intel 80386, for MS Windows

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This sample is a modular network worm. It exhibits multiple malicious behaviors including network propagation by scanning for open SMB services (TCP/445) and enumerating network shares using `WNetEnumResourceW`. It establishes persistence by creating registry Run keys. For privilege escalation, it steals the access token from a shell process like explorer.exe using `DuplicateTokenEx` to create new processes. It also includes functionality to enumerate and terminate other processes. The malware communicates with a C2 server via HTTP POST requests, and the traffic appears to be encrypted with custom cryptographic routines. A notable IOC is the construction of unusual UNC paths like `\\?\UNC\\\e-` during its network spreading routine.
